Okay 9.8 m/s/s is the acceleration of a free falling object, so just take the height in meters and multiply against 9.8 m/s/s
Now acording to airdrop wiki this would be a low-velocity airdrop. Typical height for said drop is 500 ft acording to globalsecurity.org. 152.4 meters is 500 ft. So the cargo hits the ground at around 1493.52 m/s. That in feet would be around 4900 ft/s or 3340.909 miles per hour. Granted There would be other factors in play such as air resistance and the parachute partially working
TLDR: around 3,340 miles per hour they hit the ground
